                    </div>
                    <span>For those of you who want a detailed and in-depth review of the shameful pseudo-science behind this book would do well to read the article in the May 2005 issue of Audubon.
<br />
<br />http://magazine.audubon.org/profile/profile0505.html</span>
                  
                    <div class="CustomerReviewSummary">kudos for Crichton</div>
                    <div>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Rating: </span>
                      <span>5</span>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Helpful: </span>
                      <span>1</span>
                      /
                      <span>1</span>
                      votes <span class="ItemCaption">Reviewed: </span>
                      <span>2005-05-20</span>
                    </div>
                    <span>With this book, Michael Crichton proves that he has created a legitimate new literary form: the science adventure.  His books have always ended up in a wilderness between science fiction and adventure/suspense, not inventive enough to please SF fans or taut enough to be memorable adventures.
<br />
<br />State of Fear breaks through by making science the core of the story in a way that no fiction writer has done before - and it works.  It most fiction, science shows up (if at all) as a plot device or a fluffy filler for incomplete characterization.  But here the focus is on the facts and practice of environmental science.  The thin but inoffensive plot and characterization draw the reader from one fascinating technical point after another.
<br />
<br />The technical content is solid and satisfying. The author's thorough research is evident on every page (whether or not one checks the footnotes).  State of Fear is a page turner because of the shear number of fascinating examples of risk mongering.  In each case, Crichton locates the core of the argument and explains it clearly.  
<br />
<br />This is not an anti-environment book.  On the contrary, it is a tract for the application of science to public policy.  It also happens to be a breakthrough book for science in popular literature.</span>
                  
                    <div class="CustomerReviewSummary">Made me want to go read a real book</div>
                    <div>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Rating: </span>
                      <span>2</span>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Helpful: </span>
                      <span>1</span>
                      /
                      <span>6</span>
                      votes <span class="ItemCaption">Reviewed: </span>
                      <span>2005-05-19</span>
                    </div>
                    <span>I found "State of Fear" to be truly inspirational -- when I finished it, I was inspired to go read a real novel. Or a real non-fiction book. Either one, because this mess is neither. 
<br />
<br />It starts off as tons of fun, like the best of Crichton's work. Sure, there's his usual tendency to flatten some characters into near non-existence: there's a Nepali character who vanishes for pages and pages, only to magically appear when needed to hack an evil computer or rescue one of the intrepid (caucasian) heroes.  His  name is Sanjong but it might as well be Trusty Asian Sidekick. But what the heck, it's an adventure story, not Shakespeare. 
<br />
<br />Crichton also makes some baffling choices. For example, he actually interrupts the narrative to explain the story of the Trojan Horse. Does he think that we are that ignorant, or is this information new and fascinating to him? Best not to ask.
<br />
<br />The book ultimately fails, however, because Crichton can't resist the urge to lecture. Whole chapters are devoted to these lectures, complete with charts (badly drawn charts, at that; you'd think that Harper Collins could have tossed a few bucks to a decent information designer), graphs, and footnotes. I have two problems with these lectures:
<br />
<br />1. A better novelist would have been able to make the same case within the action, characters, and language of the story.
<br />2. Crichton is not a very good lecturer. He's like that professor in college that you knew had a point buried somewhere in his pedantic recitation of data and shrill defense against his critics; someone you really wanted to pay attention to, because that point might be on the test, someone...who...you know...zzzzzzzzzzzzzzzzzz.
<br />
<br />Hollywood almost always makes movies of Michael Crichton books. If you want the story without the lectures, my advice is to wait for the film.</span>
                  
              
